        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Map Windows Symbol font code points (0xf0xx range) to their Unicode equivalents — corrects garbled text from legacy .doc/.docx documents that use Symbol encoding. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Font glyph substitution — Windows Symbol → Unicode character mapping. \par \b Input\/ \:  None (static dictionary evaluated at import time). \par \b Output\/ \:  Dict[str, str] — hex code point → Unicode character. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(0): None — pure data module] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>windows_mapping ALWAYS contains string keys (hex) and string values (Unicode chars). \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why a separate module for font mapping? A: The mapping table is large and format-specific — isolation keeps the docx reader code clean and makes the mapping auditable. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Added SEMANTIC TEMPLATE markup.] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>DATA [10][Windows Symbol → Unicode glyph mapping] =&gt; windows_mapping \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[windows_mapping]: DocxReader (Parse) → CorrectEncoding(text) → UnicodeText </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
